[
    {
        "start": 0.0,
        "end": 5.26,
        "text": "If I ask you to create a hierarchy between Kali, Kamakhya Devi and Tripura Sundari.",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 5.58,
        "end": 7.18,
        "text": "So look at the phases of the boon.",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 7.3,
        "end": 9.62,
        "text": "Maa Kali is Amavasya, Tripura Sundari is Poornima.",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 9.76,
        "end": 12.84,
        "text": "Can you say that I will have Amavasya and I will not have Poornima? You will have both.",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": true
    },
    {
        "start": 12.98,
        "end": 14.82,
        "text": "And Kamakhya is both, all of these together.",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 14.96,
        "end": 19.6,
        "text": "She changes her forms, whereas there is a way of worshipping her as Tripura Sundari,",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 19.7,
        "end": 21.1,
        "text": "there is a way of worshipping her as Kali.",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 21.18,
        "end": 24.32,
        "text": "There are other iconographies which show her with six faces.",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 24.58,
        "end": 28.2,
        "text": "And each of these are, there is Durga insider, there is Chandika insider,",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 28.2,
        "end": 30.28,
        "text": "there is Kameshwari insider.",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 30.759999999999998,
        "end": 36.74,
        "text": "Kamakhya, that Roopa, is described as in the Kalikapura as the boon giving form of her.",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 36.96,
        "end": 39.42,
        "text": "So she is in a very happy state.",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 39.7,
        "end": 42.62,
        "text": "It's described like a young girl who has been married with somebody she likes",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 42.62,
        "end": 45.16,
        "text": "and the first night after consummation of marriage,",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 45.7,
        "end": 48.14,
        "text": "when she is in an extremely happy mood, that is Kamakhya.",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 48.44,
        "end": 50.64,
        "text": "Whatever is asked in that mood, she will give you.",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 50.94,
        "end": 53.96,
        "text": "And then the next moment she can pick up the sword and she can become Chandika.",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 54.2,
        "end": 54.64,
        "text": "Chandika.",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 55.04,
        "end": 56.1,
        "text": "Chandi, which is Durga.",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    },
    {
        "start": 56.1,
        "end": 58.96,
        "text": "So the same Kamakhya can become multiple forms.",
        "pause_after": false,
        "tonal_change": false
    }
]